es as “victims” and more inclined to fight back.Battle Cries is an eye-opening examination of African American women's experiences with intimate partner abuse, the methods used to contend with abusive mates, and the immediate and enduring consequences resulting from the maltreatment. Based on intensive interviews with 40 African American women abused by their male partners, Potter's analysis takes into account variations in their experiences based on socioeconomic class, education level, and age, and discusses the common abuses and perceptions they share. Combining her remarkable findings with black feminist thought and critical race theory, Potter offers a unique and significant window through which we can better understand this understudied though rampant social problem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAbused womenzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aAfrican American womenxAbuse ofvCase studies. 0aIntimate partner violencezUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aAfrican.  aAmerican.  aabuse.  aabusive.  aconsequences.  acontend.  aenduring.  aexamination.  aexperiences.  aeye-opening.  afrom.  aimmediate.  aintimate.  amaltreatment.  amates.  amethods.  apartner.  aresulting.  aused.  awith.  awomens.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081476729040uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814768471.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814768471423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814768471/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL